# NotiFlow

Multi-tenant notification delivery platform. Companies integrate via API key to send email, webhook, and SMS notifications to their users. Built to demonstrate production-grade backend architecture.

## Architecture

```
Tenant → API Gateway (Go/Gin)
              ↓ Redis: rate limit + auth cache
         ┌────┴──────────┐
  Notification Svc    Template Svc    Subscription Svc
         └────┬──────────┘
              ↓ Kafka (MSK)
  ┌───────────┼───────────┬──────────────┐
Email     Webhook       SMS           Audit
Consumer  Consumer    Consumer       Consumer
  ↓           ↓           ↓               ↓
 SES       HTTP POST   SNS/Twilio    Postgres metrics
              ↓
           Postgres (RDS) — delivery logs, state
```

## Stack

| Layer | Technology | Why |
|---|---|---|
| API services | Go/Gin | Fast, typed, low memory |
| Event bus | Kafka (MSK) | Durable, replayable, fan-out |
| Cache & rate limiting | Redis (ElastiCache) | Sub-ms auth checks, idempotency |
| Database | Postgres (RDS) | Relational audit trail, tenant isolation |
| Container orchestration | Kubernetes (EKS) | HPA scaling, RBAC, network policies |
| Infrastructure | Terraform | Reproducible one-command deploy |
| Observability | Prometheus + Grafana | Consumer lag, delivery rate, p99 latency |

## Key design decisions

**Why Kafka instead of SQS?**
Kafka gives us consumer group replay — if the email consumer crashes mid-batch, it restarts from the last committed offset. SQS would require manual DLQ processing. The audit topic also lets us run two consumer groups on the same stream (delivery + analytics) without duplicating publishes.

**Why Redis for rate limiting?**
`INCR + EXPIRE` is atomic and sub-millisecond. A Postgres-based rate limiter would serialize all requests through the DB. Redis fails open (auth falls back to Postgres) so a Redis outage doesn't take down the API.

**Why explicit offset commit?**
`CommitInterval: 0` disables auto-commit. The consumer only commits after a successful SES call and DB write. A failed delivery does not commit — Kafka redelivers. This gives at-least-once delivery semantics without a separate retry queue.

**Idempotency key flow**
`SetNX` (atomic check-and-set) on the idempotency key prevents duplicate sends on client retries. Key expires after 24h. Returns HTTP 200 (not 409) on duplicate — client-friendly.

## Running locally

```bash
# Start Kafka + Redis + Postgres
docker-compose up -d

# Run migrations
migrate -path db/migrations -database $DATABASE_URL up

# Start a service
go run ./services/notification/...

# Start email consumer
go run ./consumers/email/...
```

## Deploying

```bash
cd infra/terraform
terraform init
terraform apply -var env=dev

# Apply K8s manifests
kubectl apply -f infra/k8s/
```

## Observability

Each service exposes `/metrics` on port 9090. Key Grafana dashboards:
- Kafka consumer lag per topic
- Delivery success rate per channel per tenant
- Redis cache hit rate
- p99 API gateway latency